-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -1.338ex; width:9.822ex; height:3.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \te=
xtstyle 1=3D{\tfrac {2\pi {\text{ rad}}}{360^{\circ }}}}"></span>=E2=81=A0<=
/span>. Multiplying both sides by <span class=3D"texhtml">360=C2=B0</span> =
gives <span class=3D"texhtml">360=C2=B0 =3D 2<i>=CF=80</i> rad</span>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Unit_symbol">Unit symbol</h=
3></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Bureau_of_Wei=
ghts_and_Measures" title=3D"International Bureau of Weights and Measures">I=
nternational Bureau of Weights and Measures</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-6"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Orga=
nization_for_Standardization" title=3D"International Organization for Stand=
ardization">International Organization for Standardization</a><sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radi=
an#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> specify <b>rad</b> as the symbol for the radian.=
 Alternative symbols that were in use in 1909 are <sup>c</sup> (the supersc=
ript letter c, for "circular measure"), the letter r, or a superscript <sup=
>R</sup>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hall_1909_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-Hall_1909-8"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> but =
these variants are infrequently used, as they may be mistaken for a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Degree_symbol" title=3D"Degree symbol">de=
gree symbol</a> (=C2=B0) or a radius (r). Hence an angle of 1.2 radians wou=
ld be written today as 1.2&nbsp;rad; archaic notations include 1.2&nbsp;r, =
1.2<sup>rad</sup>, 1.2<sup>c</sup>, or 1.2<sup>R</sup>.
</p><p>In mathematical writing, the symbol "rad" is often omitted. When qua=
ntifying an angle in the absence of any symbol, radians are assumed, and wh=
en degrees are meant, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Degree_s=
ign" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Degree sign">degree sign</a> <span clas=
s=3D"nounderlines" style=3D"border: 1px solid var(--border-color-muted,#ddd=
); color: var(--color-base,#202122); background-color: var( --background-co=
lor-neutral-subtle, #fdfdfd); padding: 1px 1px;">=C2=B0</span> is used.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Dimensional_analysis">Dimen=
sional analysis</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#As_an_SI_unit">=
=C2=A7&nbsp;As an SI unit</a></div>
<p>Plane angle may be defined as <span class=3D"texhtml"><i><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%CE%98" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=CE=98">=
=CE=B8</a></i> =3D <i>s</i>/<i>r</i></span>, where <span class=3D"texhtml m=
var" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B8</span> is the magnitude in radians=
 of the subtended angle, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">s</span> is circular arc length, and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" s=
tyle=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> is radius. One radian corresponds to t=
he angle for which <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i> =3D <i>r</i></span>, he=
nce <span class=3D"texhtml">1 radian =3D 1&nbsp;m/m =3D 1</span>.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R=
adian#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, <span class=3D"texhtml">rad</span> i=
s only to be used to express angles, not to express ratios of lengths in ge=
neral.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEInternational_Bureau_of_Weights_and_Measu=
res2019151_10-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Radian#cite_note-FOOTNOTEInternational_Bureau_of_Weights_and_Measures201=
9151-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> A similar calculation using <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Circular_sector#Area" title=3D"Circular sector">the area of =
a circular sector</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=B8</i> =3D 2<i>A</i>/<=
i>r</i><sup>2</sup></span> gives 1 radian as 1&nbsp;m<sup>2</sup>/m<sup>2</=
sup> =3D 1.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The key fact is that =
the radian is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimensionless_unit=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dimensionless unit">dimensionless unit</a>=
 equal to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1" title=3D"1">1</a>. In=
 SI 2019, the SI radian is defined accordingly as <span class=3D"nowrap">1 =
rad =3D 1</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It is a long-es=
tablished practice in mathematics and across all areas of science to make u=
se of <span class=3D"texhtml">rad =3D 1</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTE=
International_Bureau_of_Weights_and_Measures2019137_13-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-FOOTNOTEIntern=
ational_Bureau_of_Weights_and_Measures2019137-13"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radi=
an#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Giacomo Prando writes "the current state of affairs leads inevitably=
 to ghostly appearances and disappearances of the radian in the dimensional=
 analysis of physical equations".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-15"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 For example, an object hanging by a string from a pulley will rise or drop=
 by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>y</i> =3D <i>r=CE=B8</i></span> centimetres,=
 where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> i=
s the magnitude of the radius of the pulley in centimetres and <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B8</span> is the magnitu=
de of the angle through which the pulley turns in radians. When multiplying=
 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">r</span> by <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B8</span>, the un=
it radian does not appear in the product, nor does the unit centimetre=E2=
=80=94because both factors are magnitudes (numbers). Similarly in the formu=
la for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angular_velocity" title=
=3D"Angular velocity">angular velocity</a> of a rolling wheel, <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=89</i> =3D <i>v</i>/<i>r</i></span>, radians appear in =
the units of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=
=89</span> but not on the right hand side.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-16"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> Anthony French calls this phenomenon "a perennial problem in the =
teaching of mechanics".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Oberhofe=
r says that the typical advice of ignoring radians during dimensional analy=
sis and adding or removing radians in units according to convention and con=
textual knowledge is "pedagogically unsatisfying".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_not=
e-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1993 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Associ=
ation_of_Physics_Teachers" title=3D"American Association of Physics Teacher=
s">American Association of Physics Teachers</a> Metric Committee specified =
that the radian should explicitly appear in quantities only when different =
numerical values would be obtained when other angle measures were used, suc=
h as in the quantities of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angle_me=
asure" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Angle measure">angle measure</a> (rad=
), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angular_speed" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Angular speed">angular speed</a> (rad/s), <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angular_acceleration" title=3D"Angular acceleration"=
>angular acceleration</a> (rad/s<sup>2</sup>), and <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Torsion_constant#Torsional_Rigidity_(GJ)_and_Stiffness_(GJ=
/L)" title=3D"Torsion constant">torsional stiffness</a> (N=E2=8B=85m/rad), =
and not in the quantities of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Torqu=
e" title=3D"Torque">torque</a> (N=E2=8B=85m) and <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Angular_momentum" title=3D"Angular momentum">angular momentu=
m</a> (kg=E2=8B=85m<sup>2</sup>/s).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-19"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>
</p><p>At least a dozen scientists between 1936 and 2022 have made proposal=
s to treat the radian as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Base_un=
it_of_measurement" title=3D"Base unit of measurement">base unit of measurem=
ent</a> for a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Base_quantity" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Base quantity">base quantity</a> (and dimension) =
of "plane angle".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-FOOTNOTEMohrPhillips2015_21-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMohrPhillips2015-21"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Quincey_22-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-Quincey-22"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Quincey's r=
eview of proposals outlines two classes of proposal. The first option chang=
es the unit of a radius to meters per radian, but this is incompatible with=
 dimensional analysis for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area=
_of_a_circle" title=3D"Area of a circle">area of a circle</a>, <span class=
=3D"texhtml">=CF=80<i>r</i><sup>2</sup></span>. The other option is to intr=
oduce a dimensional constant. According to Quincey this approach is "logica=
lly rigorous" compared to SI, but requires "the modification of many famili=
ar mathematical and physical equations".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEQuincey=
2016_23-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rad=
ian#cite_note-FOOTNOTEQuincey2016-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A dimensional constant fo=
r angle is "rather strange" and the difficulty of modifying equations to ad=
d the dimensional constant is likely to preclude widespread use.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-Quincey_22-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-Quincey-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In particular, Quincey identifies Torrens' proposal to introduce a c=
onstant <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%CE%97" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
=CE=97">=CE=B7</a></span> equal to 1 inverse radian (1&nbsp;rad<sup>=E2=88=
=921</sup>) in a fashion similar to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Vacuum_permittivity#Historical_origin_of_the_parameter_%CE%B50" title=
=3D"Vacuum permittivity">introduction of the constant <i>=CE=B5</i><sub>0</=
sub></a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEQuincey2016_23-1" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-FOOTNOTEQuincey20=
16-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>a<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> With this chang=
e the formula for the angle subtended at the center of a circle, <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i> =3D <i>r=CE=B8</i></span>, is modified to become <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i> =3D <i>=CE=B7r=CE=B8</i></span>, and the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taylor_series" title=3D"Taylor series"=
>Taylor series</a> for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sine" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sine">sine</a> of an angle <span class=3D"tex=
html mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=B8</span> becomes:<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-Quincey_22-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Radian#cite_note-Quincey-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTE=
Torrens1986_25-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Radian#cite_note-FOOTNOTETorrens1986-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
