<p>In a similar spirit, if angles are involved, mathematically important re=
lationships between the sine and cosine functions and the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_function" title=3D"Exponential function=
">exponential function</a> (see, for example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Euler%27s_formula" title=3D"Euler's formula">Euler's formula</a=
>) can be elegantly stated when the functions' arguments are angles express=
ed in radians (and messy otherwise). More generally, in complex-number theo=
ry, the arguments of these functions are (dimensionless, possibly complex) =
numbers=E2=80=94without any reference to physical angles at all.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Physics">Physics</h3></div>
<p>The radian is widely used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ph=
ysics" title=3D"Physics">physics</a> when angular measurements are required=
. For example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angular_velocity" t=
itle=3D"Angular velocity">angular velocity</a> is typically expressed in th=
e unit <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian_per_second" title=3D=
"Radian per second">radian per second</a> (rad/s). One revolution per secon=
d corresponds to 2<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"=
>=CF=80</span> radians per second.
</p><p>Similarly, the unit used for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Angular_acceleration" title=3D"Angular acceleration">angular acceleration=
</a> is often radian per second per second (rad/s<sup>2</sup>).
</p><p>For the purpose of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimensio=
nal_analysis" title=3D"Dimensional analysis">dimensional analysis</a>, the =
units of angular velocity and angular acceleration are s<sup>=E2=88=921</su=
p> and s<sup>=E2=88=922</sup> respectively.
</p><p>Likewise, the phase angle difference of two waves can also be expres=
sed using the radian as the unit. For example, if the phase angle differenc=
e of two waves is (<span class=3D"nowrap"><i>n</i> =C3=97 2<span class=3D"t=
exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span></span>) radians, wh=
ere <i>n</i> is an integer, they are considered to be in <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phase_(waves)" title=3D"Phase (waves)">phase</a>, wh=
ilst if the phase angle difference of two waves is (<span class=3D"nowrap">=
<i>n</i> =C3=97 2<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
=CF=80</span> + <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
=CF=80</span></span>) radians, with <i>n</i> an integer, they are considere=
d to be in antiphase.
</p><p>A unit of reciprocal radian or inverse radian (rad<sup>=E2=88=921</s=
up>) is involved in derived units such as meter per radian (for <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angular_wavelength" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Angular wavelength">angular wavelength</a>) or newton-metre per radia=
n (for torsional stiffness).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Prefixes_and_variants">Pref=
ixes and variants</h3></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_prefix" title=3D"Metric =
prefix">Metric prefixes</a> for submultiples are used with radians. A <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Milliradian" title=3D"Milliradian">mill=
iradian</a> (mrad) is a thousandth of a radian (0.001&nbsp;rad), i.e. <span=
 class=3D"nowrap">1 rad =3D 10<sup>3</sup> mrad</span>. There are 2<a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pi" title=3D"Pi"><span class=3D"texhtml m=
var" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span></a> =C3=97 1000 milliradian=
s (=E2=89=88 6283.185&nbsp;mrad) in a circle. So a milliradian is just unde=
r <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles=
:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span cla=
ss=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">6283=
</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> of the angle subtended by a full circle. Thi=
s unit of angular measurement of a circle is in common use by <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Telescopic_sight" title=3D"Telescopic sight">te=
lescopic sight</a> manufacturers using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Stadiametric_rangefinding" title=3D"Stadiametric rangefinding">(stadia=
metric) rangefinding</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reticl=
e" title=3D"Reticle">reticles</a>. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Beam_divergence" title=3D"Beam divergence">divergence</a> of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laser" title=3D"Laser">laser</a> beams is=
 also usually measured in milliradians.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angular_mil" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Angular mil">angular mil</a> is an approximation of th=
e milliradian used by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NATO" title=
=3D"NATO">NATO</a> and other military organizations in <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gun" title=3D"Gun">gunnery</a> and <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sniper#Targeting,_tactics_and_techniques" title=3D"Sn=
iper">targeting</a>. Each angular mil represents <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicat=
ed-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D=
"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">1</span><span cla=
ss=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">6400</span></span>=E2=81=A0</spa=
n> of a circle and is <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw=
-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span clas=
s=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">15</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><sp=
an class=3D"den">8</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>% or 1.875% smaller than th=
e milliradian. For the small angles typically found in targeting work, the =
convenience of using the number 6400 in calculation outweighs the small mat=
hematical errors it introduces. In the past, other gunnery systems have use=
d different approximations to <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" hr=
ef=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<s=
pan class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</s=
pan><span class=3D"den">2000<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-styl=
e:italic;">=CF=80</span></span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>; for example Sweden =
used the <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:Templat=
eStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><s=
pan class=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"de=
n">6300</span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> <i>streck</i> and the USSR used <link=
 rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r12144=
02035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"n=
um">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">6000</span>=
</span>=E2=81=A0</span>. Being based on the milliradian, the NATO mil subte=
nds roughly 1&nbsp;m at a range of 1000&nbsp;m (at such small angles, the c=
urvature is negligible).
</p><p>Prefixes smaller than milli- are useful in measuring extremely small=
 angles. Microradians (=CE=BCrad, <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-va=
lue=3D"6992100000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>10<sup>=E2=88=926</sup>&nbsp;ra=
d</span>) and nanoradians (nrad, <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-val=
ue=3D"6989100000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>10<sup>=E2=88=929</sup>&nbsp;rad=
</span>) are used in astronomy, and can also be used to measure the beam qu=
ality of lasers with ultra-low divergence. More common is the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arc_second" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Arc =
second">arc second</a>, which is <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style"=
 href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=
=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num"><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span></span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</s=
pan><span class=3D"den"><span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"700=
5648000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>648<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">000=
</span></span></span></span>=E2=81=A0</span>&nbsp;rad (around 4.8481&nbsp;m=
icroradians).
</p>
