<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Pre-20th_century">Pre-20th =
century</h3></div>
<p>The idea of measuring angles by the length of the arc was in use by math=
ematicians quite early. For example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Al-Kashi" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Al-Kashi">al-Kashi</a> (c. 1400=
) used so-called <i>diameter parts</i> as units, where one diameter part wa=
s <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles=
:r1214402035"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span cla=
ss=3D"num">1</span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">60</=
span></span>=E2=81=A0</span> radian. They also used sexagesimal subunits of=
 the diameter part.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Newton in 167=
2 spoke of "the angular quantity of a body's circular motion", but used it =
only as a relative measure to develop an astronomical algorithm.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-Roche_34-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Radian#cite_note-Roche-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The concept of <i>the</i> radian measure is normally credited to <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roger_Cotes" title=3D"Roger Cotes">Ro=
ger Cotes</a>, who died in 1716. By 1722, his cousin Robert Smith had colle=
cted and published Cotes' mathematical writings in a book, <i>Harmonia mens=
urarum</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In a chapter of edito=
rial comments, Smith gave what is probably the first published calculation =
of one radian in degrees, citing a note of Cotes that has not survived. Smi=
th described the radian in everything but name =E2=80=93 "Now this number i=
s equal to 180 degrees as the radius of a circle to the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semicircumference" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sem=
icircumference">semicircumference</a>, this is as 1 to 3.141592653589" =E2=
=80=93, and recognized its naturalness as a unit of angular measure.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Radian#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-37"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p><p>In 1765, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonhard_Euler" ti=
tle=3D"Leonhard Euler">Leonhard Euler</a> implicitly adopted the radian as =
a unit of angle.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Roche_34-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-Roche-34"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Sp=
ecifically, Euler defined angular velocity as "The angular speed in rotatio=
nal motion is the speed of that point, the distance of which from the axis =
of gyration is expressed by one."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-38"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Euler was probably the first to adopt this convention, referred to as the =
radian convention, which gives the simple formula for angular velocity <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=89</i> =3D <i>v</i>/<i>r</i></span>. As discusse=
d in <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#Dimensional_analysi=
s">=C2=A7&nbsp;Dimensional analysis</a></i>, the radian convention has been=
 widely adopted, while dimensionally consistent formulations require the in=
sertion of a dimensional constant, for example <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
=CF=89</i> =3D <i>v</i>/(<i>=CE=B7r</i>)</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOT=
EQuincey2021_28-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Radian#cite_note-FOOTNOTEQuincey2021-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Prior to the term <i>radian</i> becoming widespread, the unit was co=
mmonly called <i>circular measure</i> of an angle.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_not=
e-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> The term <i>radian</i> first appeared in print on 5 June =
1873, in examination questions set by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/James_Thomson_(engineer)" title=3D"James Thomson (engineer)">James Thom=
son</a> (brother of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lord_Kelvin" t=
itle=3D"Lord Kelvin">Lord Kelvin</a>) at <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Queen%27s_University_Belfast" title=3D"Queen's University Belfast">Q=
ueen's College</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belfast" title=
=3D"Belfast">Belfast</a>. He had used the term as early as 1871, while in 1=
869, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Muir_(mathematician)" =
title=3D"Thomas Muir (mathematician)">Thomas Muir</a>, then of the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_St_Andrews" title=3D"Univer=
sity of St Andrews">University of St Andrews</a>, vacillated between the te=
rms <i>rad</i>, <i>radial</i>, and <i>radian</i>. In 1874, after a consulta=
tion with James Thomson, Muir adopted <i>radian</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-40"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_n=
ote-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-41"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radi=
an#cite_note-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The name <i>radian</i> was not universally ado=
pted for some time after this. <i>Longmans' School Trigonometry</i> still c=
alled the radian <i>circular measure</i> when published in 1890.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-43" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R=
adian#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1893 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_Macfarlan=
e" title=3D"Alexander Macfarlane">Alexander Macfarlane</a> wrote "the true =
analytical argument for the circular ratios is not the ratio of the arc to =
the radius, but the ratio of twice the area of a sector to the square on th=
e radius."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-44" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, the paper was=
 withdrawn from the published proceedings of mathematical congress held in =
connection with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World%27s_Columbia=
n_Exposition" title=3D"World's Columbian Exposition">World's Columbian Expo=
sition</a> in Chicago (acknowledged at page 167), and privately published i=
n his <i>Papers on Space Analysis</i> (1894). Macfarlane reached this idea =
or ratios of areas while considering the basis for <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Hyperbolic_angle" title=3D"Hyperbolic angle">hyperbolic an=
gle</a> which is analogously defined.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-45" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-45"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"As_an_SI_unit">As an SI uni=
t</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#Dimensional_analy=
sis">=C2=A7&nbsp;Dimensional analysis</a></div>
<p>As Paul Quincey et al. write, "The status of angles within the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units" title=3D"I=
nternational System of Units">International System of Units</a> (SI) has lo=
ng been a source of controversy and confusion."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-46" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-4=
6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> In 1960, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genera=
l_Conference_on_Weights_and_Measures" title=3D"General Conference on Weight=
s and Measures">General Conference on Weights and Measures</a> (CGPM) estab=
lished the SI and the radian was classified as a "supplementary unit" along=
 with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steradian" title=3D"Ster=
adian">steradian</a>. This special class was officially regarded "either as=
 base units or as derived units", as the CGPM could not reach a decision on=
 whether the radian was a base unit or a derived unit.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4=
7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite=
_note-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> Richard Nelson writes "This ambiguity [in the classif=
ication of the supplemental units] prompted a spirited discussion over thei=
r proper interpretation."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Nelson_48-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-Nelson-48"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> In May 1980 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consultat=
ive_Committee_for_Units" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Consultative Commit=
tee for Units">Consultative Committee for Units</a> (CCU) considered a prop=
osal for making radians an SI base unit, using a constant <span class=3D"te=
xhtml"><i>=CE=B1</i><sub>0</sub> =3D 1 rad</span>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_not=
e-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEQuincey2021_28-2" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-FOOTNOTEQ=
uincey2021-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> but turned it down to avoid an upheaval to curre=
nt practice.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEQuincey2021_28-3" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-FOOTNOTEQuince=
y2021-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In October 1980 the CGPM decided that supplementary units were dimen=
sionless derived units for which the CGPM allowed the freedom of using them=
 or not using them in expressions for SI derived units,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
Nelson_48-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R=
adian#cite_note-Nelson-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> on the basis that "[no formalism] ex=
ists which is at the same time coherent and convenient and in which the qua=
ntities plane angle and solid angle might be considered as base quantities"=
 and that "[the possibility of treating the radian and steradian as SI base=
 units] compromises the internal coherence of the SI based on only seven ba=
se units".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEInternational_Bureau_of_Weights_and_M=
easures2019174=E2=80=93175_50-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-FOOTNOTEInternational_Bureau_of_Weights=
_and_Measures2019174%E2%80%93175-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4=
9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In 1995 the CGPM eliminate=
d the class of supplementary units and defined the radian and the steradian=
 as "dimensionless derived units, the names and symbols of which may, but n=
eed not, be used in expressions for other SI derived units, as is convenien=
t".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEInternational_Bureau_of_Weights_and_Measures=
2019179_51-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Radian#cite_note-FOOTNOTEInternational_Bureau_of_Weights_and_Measures201917=
9-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> Mikhail Kalinin writing in 2019 has criticized the 1980 C=
GPM decision as "unfounded" and says that the 1995 CGPM decision used incon=
sistent arguments and introduced "numerous discrepancies, inconsistencies, =
and contradictions in the wordings of the SI".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-52=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p><p>At the 2013 meeting of the CCU, Peter Mohr gave a presentation on al=
leged inconsistencies arising from defining the radian as a dimensionless u=
nit rather than a base unit. CCU President Ian M. Mills declared this to be=
 a "formidable problem" and the <i>CCU Working Group on Angles and Dimensio=
nless Quantities in the SI</i> was established.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-53" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-5=
3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> The CCU met in 2021, but did not reach a consensus. A small =
number of members argued strongly that the radian should be a base unit, bu=
t the majority felt the status quo was acceptable or that the change would =
cause more problems than it would solve. A task group was established to "r=
eview the historical use of SI supplementary units and consider whether rei=
ntroduction would be of benefit", among other activities.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-54" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#c=
ite_note-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-55" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radian#cite_note-55"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
